00:01:12.300 --> 00:01:19.580
So when we're teaching,
we are getting

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:21.620
a sense of how our
students are learning

00:01:21.620 --> 00:01:23.310
through various
types of assessments

00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:25.440
we might be giving them--

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:28.490
writing papers, tests.

00:01:28.490 --> 00:01:30.350
And yet, it's quite
likely that you still

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:32.734
have a lot of questions about
your students' learning.

00:01:32.734 --> 00:01:33.650
What are they getting?

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:35.066
What are they
having trouble with?

00:01:35.066 --> 00:01:37.190
What kinds of
misconceptions do they have?

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:38.720
How are they
approaching learning?

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:42.840
So there's always questions
about student learning.

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:45.770
One approach to looking
at how students learn

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:47.750
and student learning
in our classrooms

00:01:47.750 --> 00:01:50.190
is called the scholarship
of teaching and learning,

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:53.351
which is often
referred to as SOTL.

00:01:53.351 --> 00:01:58.340
And this is really thinking
about a systematic inquiry

00:01:58.340 --> 00:02:00.129
of student learning
in your own classroom.

00:02:00.129 --> 00:02:01.670
And so that's
important, is that this

00:02:01.670 --> 00:02:05.030
doesn't have to be done
by some outside expert,

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:07.010
but that you as a
practitioner can actually

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:08.660
be studying student learning.

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:11.360
And a way to think about it
is that, if you are a faculty

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:13.730
member and you're doing
research, scholarly research,

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:15.860
in your own field, you're
going to be thinking

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:17.530
about problems and questions.

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:19.280
And you're going to
be thinking about ways

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:22.740
of collecting evidence, and ways
of interpreting that evidence.

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:25.927
And you can do the same kind
of thing in your classroom.

00:02:25.927 --> 00:02:28.010
You can be asking questions
about student learning

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:29.630
and about teaching.

00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:32.630
You can be collecting evidence
about student learning.

00:02:32.630 --> 00:02:35.270
And the goal here
is really to improve

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:36.780
the quality of education.

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:39.357
So as the title
is, we're learning

00:02:39.357 --> 00:02:41.690
about student learning for
the sake of improving student

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:43.590
learning.

00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:46.220
So what we're going to be
doing in the session today is,

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:48.890
we have two speakers who
are going to talk about some

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:52.850
of their own experiences
with collecting information

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:55.660
and evidence about
student learning.

00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:57.620
So we have two case studies.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.490
And after that we'll be doing
some individual and group

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:04.490
work, thinking about how we
might do some of these things

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:05.000
on our own.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.220
How might we ask
our own questions

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:10.340
and start collecting
some data ourselves?

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:21.030
So I'm pleased to introduce our
first speaker, Henrike Besche.

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:23.640
She received her
PhD in Biochemistry

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:26.520
in Germany in 2004,
and since then she

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:29.460
has been here at Harvard
Medical School in Cell Biology,

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:31.320
first as a postdoctoral
fellow and then

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:32.975
as a curriculum fellow.

00:03:32.975 --> 00:03:34.350
When she was a
curriculum fellow,

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:36.808
she became involved with medical
education and the Pathways

00:03:36.808 --> 00:03:40.440
curriculum, which is a flipped
discussion-based curriculum

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:45.430
launched at the
med school in 2015.

00:03:45.430 --> 00:03:47.310
She is now working
as associate director

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:48.807
of curriculum integration.

00:03:48.807 --> 00:03:50.640
She's teaching for three
months of the year,

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:52.223
and the rest of the
time she's focused

00:03:52.223 --> 00:03:54.450
on improving basic
science curriculum

00:03:54.450 --> 00:03:57.090
across the entire four
years of the MD program.

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:58.890
I'm going to turn
it over to her now.

00:03:58.890 --> 00:04:00.450
Thanks, Tamara.

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.970
I'm actually teaching right
now, so this is my retreat

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:04.480
for like a day.

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:07.150
But where's the slide advancer?

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:08.850
So I'm going to give
you one example.

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:12.150
I really love using
data to figure out

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:14.370
how our teaching is
going, and today there's

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:17.410
one story I wanted
to share with you.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:19.895
So just to briefly
give you some context,

00:04:19.895 --> 00:04:21.269
we're going to
focus on teamwork,

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:23.910
but I thought it wouldn't make
much sense unless I introduced

00:04:23.910 --> 00:04:25.826
to you a little bit about
what we're currently

00:04:25.826 --> 00:04:27.150
doing at the medical school.

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:30.750
So not very long ago,
teaching at our school

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:32.700
simply pretty much
looked like this picture

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:35.900
from the 1940s in
Albany Medical School,

00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:39.390
so lectures, lectures,
and more lectures.

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:43.710
And if you went into a
lecture hall recently,

00:04:43.710 --> 00:04:46.164
you would look down, people
were on their screens.

00:04:46.164 --> 00:04:48.330
At least a third of the
students doing other things,

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:49.871
and the other
two-thirds were at home

00:04:49.871 --> 00:04:52.710
sleeping, because they could
watch that thing online later.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:54.270
So we realized
there really wasn't

00:04:54.270 --> 00:04:56.125
much of an intellectual
exchange going

00:04:56.125 --> 00:04:57.750
on that would justify
to actually bring

00:04:57.750 --> 00:04:59.730
students and faculty together.

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:02.430
So we decided to just
not do that anymore.

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:04.210
But what do you do instead?

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:07.710
So instead, now we have a
discussion-based curriculum

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:08.550
in these classrooms.

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:10.680
It's actually a picture
from our classroom.

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:13.320
You can see students
sitting at these tables.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.850
You have, on this
image, actually

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:16.530
three faculty
members in the room

00:05:16.530 --> 00:05:18.910
engaging with those students.

00:05:18.910 --> 00:05:23.160
So we adopt this pedagogy, CBCL,
or case-based collaborative

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:23.670
learning.

00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.940
And it started in 2015.

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:28.530
So I just wanted to
dissect what that

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:30.030
means for you a
little more before I

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:32.160
dive into the teamwork.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:34.680
So "flipped" means
students study

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:35.840
before they come to class.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:38.340
Class is now mandatory for them.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:40.290
And it's case-based
in the sense that,

00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:42.240
throughout their first
year of medical school,

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:45.210
it becomes increasingly
actually based on patient cases.

00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:49.470
But you could also extrapolate
and frame it as problem-based.

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:51.510
So we typically give
them application problems

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:53.880
that stretch and deepen the
kind of content they were

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:56.040
exposed to in the prep work.

00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:57.330
And it's collaborative.

00:05:57.330 --> 00:05:59.610
Students are working
in tables of four.

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:01.320
So these tables of
four are the teams

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:03.719
I'm going to refer to
throughout the presentation.

00:06:03.719 --> 00:06:05.010
And then it's discussion-based.

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:08.220
So this discussion goes
through an alternating rhythm

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:10.879
of talking with their team,
talking amongst peers,

00:06:10.879 --> 00:06:13.170
back to discussing with the
larger group with a faculty

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:14.440
member.

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.840
So we did this.

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:18.030
We pretty much pulled
the rug out on lectures.

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:21.320
And as you can imagine,
implementation wasn't smooth.

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:23.880
Overall, successful,
but we definitely

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:26.980
had an intense phase of
learning from our students,

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:29.250
what was working and
what wasn't working.

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:32.850
And initially when we flipped,
workload was a gigantic story.

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:35.070
I mean, all these expert
faculty front-loading

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:37.470
all their expert
knowledge was pretty much

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:41.210
leading to prep times that were
absolutely not sustainable.

00:06:41.210 --> 00:06:44.520
Case-based, it's actually
not easy to decide what makes

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:46.170
a good classroom discussion.

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:48.330
Things was yes or no
answers are pretty dead

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:49.540
the moment you ask them.

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:53.670
So there was a lot of
work that went into that.

00:06:53.670 --> 00:06:56.040
Not soon into the curriculum,
about a year in, I

00:06:56.040 --> 00:06:58.080
started to hear
a lot of students

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:02.100
on the side talking about mixed
experiences in their team.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:06.780
So that's what got started what
I'm going to present today.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:08.970
And then one big
piece of focus right

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:10.510
now is actually facilitation.

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:13.080
So we have recently launched
a peer-coaching program

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:16.960
to have faculty actually become
even better facilitators.

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:18.870
So I could talk to any of those.

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:22.890
If anyone's interested, please
let me know after the session.

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:25.380
But today I'm going to focus
on the teamwork, with a focus

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:28.410
on, how do we get the data
to actually figure out

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.820
what's going on?

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:33.330
So again, this is
the CBCL classroom.

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:36.210
And I need you to understand
this scheme, which

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:39.600
is the CBCL classroom, of
which we have four running

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:43.260
at the same time with
around 44 or 43 students

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:44.880
sitting at 11 tables of four.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:47.220
So every green square
is one of these tables

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:48.990
with four students.

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:50.580
Typically one or three faculty.

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:53.280
It really depends on the course
or the kind of session you run.

00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:55.410
And again, times four.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:08:01.080
So when we started out, faculty
envisioned, this is what it is.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:05.100
Everyone's green,
content, happy, satisfied,

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.270
has a great experience.

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:09.900
In fact, we haven't given
the team part any thought.

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:12.240
Faculty were totally
focused on content delivery.

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:16.940
Teams, they just
happened to work.

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:20.860
And anecdotally, I learned
that might not be the case.

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:23.460
So in conversations
with students,

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:26.100
I realized some students
had a terrible experience

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:26.680
occasionally.

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:28.680
They really were sitting
with people they really

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:31.590
didn't get along with, and then
they were just sitting it out.

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:33.809
Or they had a so-so experience.

00:08:33.809 --> 00:08:35.760
They all had great tables.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:36.850
Don't get me wrong.

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:39.630
But they all had
terrible tables, too.

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:41.370
But the more I talked
to people, the less

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:43.710
I could put a finger on,
well, is this a problem?

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:44.670
How big is the problem?

00:08:44.670 --> 00:08:46.019
Am I making the problem up?

00:08:46.019 --> 00:08:48.060
And I certainly didn't
want to make a problem up,

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:49.410
and to start bothering faculty.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:51.030
Was this a problem
if it was really

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:54.460
like 5% of the students
occasionally having a problem?

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.310
So the question was,
how do we measure this?

00:08:56.310 --> 00:08:58.420
So I looked in the
literature and found

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:02.640
a nice, 17-item, team-based
performance scale that I just

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:03.900
ran through the class.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:05.970
I asked the professor
to collaborate with me,

00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:08.610
and we made it a assignment
in one of the courses

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:11.647
to fill out that survey with
a qualitative piece to it.

00:09:11.647 --> 00:09:13.230
So there wasn't just
this scale that I

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:14.820
could turn into a
number, there was also

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:17.278
the question of what's working
in the team you're currently

00:09:17.278 --> 00:09:19.800
working with and what
could be improved.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:23.340
So I took those data and
was able to piece together

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:26.550
what I roughly consider
a representative image

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:30.330
of a typical CBCL classroom,
with orange indicating

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:33.930
significantly lesser
of a good experience

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:36.100
than the others
sitting at your table.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:37.740
So I'm looking for
a gap in experience.

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:40.560
I can't fully judge
it, but there's a gap.

00:09:40.560 --> 00:09:42.570
There was a gap in how
these individuals rated

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:43.470
that experience.

00:09:43.470 --> 00:09:45.270
The orange squares
signify people

00:09:45.270 --> 00:09:48.210
that had a lower-performing
team experience.

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:51.194
And you'd find these asymmetric
tables with one person

00:09:51.194 --> 00:09:53.610
kind of feeling isolated in
the experience, and just said,

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:55.818
this isn't working for me,
but the other three people

00:09:55.818 --> 00:09:57.420
had a reasonably good time.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:09:59.610
You'll see the split
tables with a couple

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:02.910
of people feeling great, and
the other too often feeling

00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:04.080
excluded.

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:07.230
And then occasionally you'd
see this big orange blob,

00:10:07.230 --> 00:10:12.780
which is what I call a toxic
table, with cognitive biases,

00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:16.830
emotions running really high,
like really bad stuff happening

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:21.760
that didn't seem
conducive to learning.

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:23.782
So that's where we arrived.

00:10:23.782 --> 00:10:25.740
But then I was really
happy I made the decision

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:28.950
to not just ask about those
quantifiable questions,

00:10:28.950 --> 00:10:31.707
but also ask what was working
and what was not working.

00:10:31.707 --> 00:10:33.540
Because what I needed
to know, what would it

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:35.850
take to make this better?

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:40.270
So this is what I learned
from reading those comments.

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:43.860
So I did a pretty brief,
qualitative type of analysis,

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:45.630
and three big domains
stuck out to me.

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:46.800
It was emotions.

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:48.840
How did you feel in that team?

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:51.390
It was whether or not that team
had a way of working together

00:10:51.390 --> 00:10:54.390
to kind of process, and how they
actually talked to each other,

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:56.010
how they communicated.

00:10:56.010 --> 00:11:00.270
And so in a good team, in a
good classroom experience,

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:01.994
they felt safe and valued.

00:11:01.994 --> 00:11:03.660
Often they would
actually have a process

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:07.680
to go around and elicit
everyone's opinion explicitly.

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:09.987
So they were not just
haphazardly talking

00:11:09.987 --> 00:11:10.570
at each other.

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:12.390
They were systematic about it.

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:14.490
Another big thing is
respecting that everybody

00:11:14.490 --> 00:11:15.960
thinks at a different pace.

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:18.270
So they were actually adamant
about giving each other

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:21.540
that space to think quietly
before starting to talk,

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.040
or they would use
different methods.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:26.010
They wouldn't just talk, but
they would draw things out

00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:27.570
on boards and such.

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:30.810
And that kind of
process also seemed

00:11:30.810 --> 00:11:33.540
to help with valuing
everyone's opinion.

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:35.790
So it's not like they asked
everyone to say something.

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:39.780
They also valued and truly
listened, didn't interrupt,

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:43.500
and in that process we're able
to emphasize the reasoning

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:46.080
and push for deeper thinking.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:50.320
So the orange people described
a very different experience.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:54.780
So often that orange color
is associated with feeling

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.900
outright dismissed and unsafe.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:11:59.940
They complained about
side conversations that

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:01.620
make them feel excluded,
they complained

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:02.620
about a lack of process.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:06.570
So it was just pure chaos
unfolding at these tables,

00:12:06.570 --> 00:12:09.810
too much focus on
the correct answer.

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:12.480
And med students have this
famous expression of the gaana

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:14.250
mentality, so that
seemed to come out

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:16.050
in some people at these tables.

00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:19.020
Answers blurted out without any
consideration of where others

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:21.900
were in the thinking process;
lack of discourse reasoning;

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:26.100
and just not being heard;
some person dominating

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:30.090
at these tables were
common complaints.

00:12:30.090 --> 00:12:32.820
So maybe that's not
surprising, right?

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:34.680
We've all had
experiences of co-workers

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:37.020
that we just can't
stand, and meetings that,

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:41.100
if we have to sit with that
person, it's just a nightmare.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:41.670
That's fine.

00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:42.700
People will be people.

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:45.300
But I did want to know, is there
something we can do about it?

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:47.996
Because I strongly felt
that, well, maybe we just

00:12:47.996 --> 00:12:49.620
need to tell them
how to work together.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:53.514
Maybe they need to know
that you need a process.

00:12:53.514 --> 00:12:55.930
Maybe that's a thing, and if
we tell them, it gets better.

00:12:55.930 --> 00:12:57.420
So we're telling them that now.

00:12:57.420 --> 00:13:00.840
That's not the
question I tested.

00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:02.430
We're giving them
the information

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:04.763
that I just showed you, and
feed them forward right now.

00:13:04.763 --> 00:13:06.780
But at that time,
I just said, OK,

00:13:06.780 --> 00:13:10.350
why don't we give them
some time to just talk

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:13.060
about how it's going, how
they want to work together?

00:13:13.060 --> 00:13:14.610
So we gave them the time.

00:13:14.610 --> 00:13:16.920
I found another course
to collaborate with,

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:20.520
and they got 20 minutes to,
at the beginning of their team

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:23.110
work, to talk to each other,
how they want to work together,

00:13:23.110 --> 00:13:25.560
and another 20 minutes
a week or so later

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:28.680
to talk about how it was
going and make adjustments.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:31.720
And that simple act
of giving them time

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:34.470
led from what we had
looked at here, which

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:37.800
was the end status of teams
after four weeks of the course

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:40.650
without any consideration
to the team process,

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:42.600
it turned into this.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:44.670
So just to make
sure you understand,

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:45.930
these are different teams.

00:13:45.930 --> 00:13:48.780
It's not a controlled
experiment.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:51.450
But with those additional
two times, 20 minutes,

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:54.487
they were able to
overall come out

00:13:54.487 --> 00:13:56.820
just simply looking like they
were getting along better.

00:13:56.820 --> 00:13:58.444
And I'm not showing
that here, but it's

00:13:58.444 --> 00:14:02.550
not just that we prevent toxic
teams potentially by this,

00:14:02.550 --> 00:14:05.220
but the OK-functioning
teams actually

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:07.310
became high-functioning
teams, as well.

00:14:07.310 --> 00:14:08.810
So also, the green
isn't just green.

00:14:08.810 --> 00:14:12.960
There are shades of green, data
that I'm not presenting here.

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.250
So I'm calling this
my intervention group,

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:17.670
but in an experimental
design kind of sense,

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:20.640
there is no control here.

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:24.756
So to translate that back
to what we're doing at HMS,

00:14:24.756 --> 00:14:26.130
there's more that
went into this,

00:14:26.130 --> 00:14:27.960
but it led me to
conclude that what

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:30.930
we can do for our CBCL
classrooms is maybe formally

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:32.910
create times for teams
to set norms and give

00:14:32.910 --> 00:14:35.100
each other feedback
as just standard part

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:37.560
of the curriculum.

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:39.897
Now I want to pilot
peer feedback.

00:14:39.897 --> 00:14:41.730
Maybe that's something
we can fold into this

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:43.530
and further enhance
communication,

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:46.380
interpersonal skill
building, which is something

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:47.550
that I'd be excited to do.

00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:50.615
But we'd also give them maybe a
more, bigger context for that.

00:14:50.615 --> 00:14:51.990
Give them a little
more knowledge

00:14:51.990 --> 00:14:55.780
about where this
is all coming from.

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:59.130
So if you thought this is
interesting, that's great.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:01.140
I do, too, and I
love this project.

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:03.780
But that's actually not
what I wanted to talk about

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:04.740
with you in a sense.

00:15:04.740 --> 00:15:08.250
What I hope you would realize
is that this is actually

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:10.260
an example of how
you can use the mind

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:13.530
frame of continuous
quality improvement

00:15:13.530 --> 00:15:15.390
to drive what you
do in the classroom.

00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:19.290
So I've been a scientist for the
better part of my adult life,

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:22.200
and I miss the scientists,
and I'm very data driven.

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:26.400
But I've always been hindered
by hypothesis-driven research,

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:28.610
because it ends you
in a position where

00:15:28.610 --> 00:15:31.110
you have to have this control
group, and it's very limiting.

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:32.834
And doing educational
research in a way

00:15:32.834 --> 00:15:34.500
that you have that
perfect control group

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:36.810
and you have that
hypothesis, it often just

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:38.070
doesn't fit into real life.

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:40.500
And you can't withhold
entire pieces of instruction

00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:42.780
from half of the class,
and then give it to others,

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:45.250
and then test them
on the same thing.

00:15:45.250 --> 00:15:47.910
So what I hope you
can acknowledge

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:50.190
is that, in this
scenario, we move

00:15:50.190 --> 00:15:52.584
from a curriculum with
lectures and no consideration

00:15:52.584 --> 00:15:54.000
of teamwork, to
something where we

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.050
had active learning
and some teams,

00:15:56.050 --> 00:15:59.040
but no framework, to
collaboration and teamwork

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:01.740
is actually a program objective
of the medical degree, which

00:16:01.740 --> 00:16:02.760
I found out later.

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:04.160
So it fits nicely.

00:16:04.160 --> 00:16:06.030
It gives me a lot of leverage.

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:09.600
So I now aim to make
active skill-building

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:11.580
and peer feedback
really be an integrated

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:14.640
part of the curriculum, and
who knows where that leads me.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:17.430
So this is the framework of
continuous quality improvement.

00:16:17.430 --> 00:16:18.480
You're driving change.

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:22.109
You're driving that boulder
up the hill, telling people,

00:16:22.109 --> 00:16:23.400
peer feedback is a great thing.

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:24.941
Three years ago
every medical student

00:16:24.941 --> 00:16:27.600
was running away from me if I
mentioned that in the hallway.

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:29.684
And faculty were dismissing
me, saying, oh gosh,

00:16:29.684 --> 00:16:30.850
who wants to deal with that?

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:34.570
That's going to be
a social nightmare.

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:37.800
So you're not only learning
what your students might need,

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:40.840
you're also educating students
and faculty at the same time.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:43.150
So there's a dualism.

00:16:43.150 --> 00:16:45.390
So just to compare
this to research,

00:16:45.390 --> 00:16:48.420
so QI is not
hypothesis-driven, it's

00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:51.150
just about how this is going,
how we can make it better.

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:53.040
And it frees you have
these limitations

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:56.550
that often research brings in
terms of experimental design.

00:16:56.550 --> 00:16:59.430
You can do it in a more
incremental fashion

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:01.962
that, I drive this in a
kind of yearly rhythm.

00:17:01.962 --> 00:17:03.420
I figure out, what
next piece can I

00:17:03.420 --> 00:17:07.190
work out in the next six
or eight or nine months?

00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:09.730
While research, I think,
has a lot of benefit,

00:17:09.730 --> 00:17:13.890
but I've found this
framework really liberating.

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:15.869
So this wouldn't be
possible without some

00:17:15.869 --> 00:17:17.440
of the people in the room.

00:17:17.440 --> 00:17:20.730
There's the Office of
Educational Quality Improvement

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:23.890
that was just founded at
HMS, which was Amy Sullivan,

00:17:23.890 --> 00:17:26.819
Barbara Cockrill, John
Dalrymple, Carolyn over there,

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:29.670
and Steve ran that office and
have helped me out with this.

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:32.040
And then Ed Hundert
is our dean, who's

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.760
really a champion for
data-driven improvement

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:38.790
of teaching, and Randall King
is my long term collaborator.

00:17:38.790 --> 00:17:40.108
Thank you.

00:17:40.108 --> 00:17:42.044
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:44.721 --> 00:17:45.220
All right.

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:47.767
So we have time for
one or two questions.

00:17:47.767 --> 00:17:48.850
Any questions for Henrike?

00:17:51.297 --> 00:17:52.880
I'm just wondering
how you got buy-in.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.470
Because that seems like
a very dramatic change.

00:17:55.470 --> 00:17:59.840
Oh, when we changed
the curriculum?

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:01.970
I wasn't at the very
initial meetings.

00:18:01.970 --> 00:18:04.070
I was part of a
committee that created

00:18:04.070 --> 00:18:06.960
one of the latter courses
in the curriculum.

00:18:06.960 --> 00:18:09.830
And I think there was an
executive decision being

00:18:09.830 --> 00:18:11.770
made at a higher
level that we're

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:13.790
going to go through with this.

00:18:13.790 --> 00:18:16.989
And at the time I thought,
this is never going to work.

00:18:16.989 --> 00:18:18.530
They didn't give us
any instructions.

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:20.450
Because they said, we're
going to go flipped,

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:22.116
do something
discussion-based, but there

00:18:22.116 --> 00:18:23.910
wasn't like, do this kind.

00:18:23.910 --> 00:18:26.350
There was no information
how we were to do this.

00:18:26.350 --> 00:18:29.079
In retrospect, I thought
it was ingenious,

00:18:29.079 --> 00:18:30.620
because when the
faculty got together

00:18:30.620 --> 00:18:32.616
to get concretely going,
to say, how are we

00:18:32.616 --> 00:18:33.740
going to change our course?

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:36.110
There was a lot of
deliberation in the room,

00:18:36.110 --> 00:18:39.170
but we still had the freedom to
make it our own in the process.

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:42.710
And there was a lot of whining
about letting go, and fear.

00:18:42.710 --> 00:18:46.970
But overall, I think some
form of demanding change,

00:18:46.970 --> 00:18:51.420
but then giving people
creative freedom, made it work.

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:53.165
But as I said, I
wasn't at those,

00:18:53.165 --> 00:18:55.490
when that decision was
made to really go ahead,

00:18:55.490 --> 00:18:57.571
I wasn't there for that.

00:18:57.571 --> 00:18:58.070
All right.

00:18:58.070 --> 00:18:59.396
One more question.

00:18:59.396 --> 00:19:01.830
How were the original
groups formed?

00:19:01.830 --> 00:19:04.130
Oh yeah, we just
assigned them, and then

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:07.580
we rotate them and permutate
them throughout the year.

00:19:07.580 --> 00:19:09.660
Did you ever consider
not doing that and--

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.010
I would go as far
as considering that,

00:19:12.010 --> 00:19:15.440
but I think that is too
early in this process.

00:19:15.440 --> 00:19:17.030
I think we should
have longer teams,

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:19.220
and give them more support
to emotionally grow

00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:20.360
in those teams.

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:23.380
Right now, I think the most
I can ask is for four months.

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:26.090
And I'm making inroads
on longer teams.

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:30.440
But I know of one team-based
curriculum at the School of--

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:33.000
its Charlestown, Institute
of Health Professions.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.480
They have a 14-month
TBL curriculum,

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:37.119
and they lock those
in on day one.

00:19:37.119 --> 00:19:38.660
And then they have
a mediator to help

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:40.760
the teams that run
into conflict they

00:19:40.760 --> 00:19:43.500
can't resolve on their own.

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:44.000
All right.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.510
Thank you very much, Henrike.

00:19:45.510 --> 00:19:46.010
All right.

